---
import SlidesLayout from '../../../layouts/SlidesLayout.astro';
const base = (import.meta.env.BASE_URL || '').replace(/\/$/, '');
---

<SlidesLayout
  title="Communication &amp; Patient Teaching – Slides – D439 Foundations of Nursing"
  protected={true}
  backHref={`${base}/private/d439/communication-teaching`}
  backLabel="← Full Article"
>
  <div class="slides-wrapper">

    <!-- COLUMN 1: Title -->
    <div class="slide-column">
      <div class="column-inner">
        <div class="slide slide-title">
          <div class="slide-badge">D439 – Foundations of Nursing</div>
          <div class="title-icon">💬</div>
          <h1 class="slide-main-title">Communication &amp; Patient Teaching</h1>
          <h2 class="slide-subtitle">SBAR · Therapeutic Communication · Delegation · Documentation</h2>
          <p class="slide-note">← → Arrow keys or Prev / Next buttons to navigate · ↓ Arrow key for optional detail slides</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- COLUMN 2: SBAR -->
    <div class="slide-column">
      <div class="column-inner">
        <div class="slide">
          <div class="slide-number">2 / 8</div>
          <h2 class="slide-heading">📋 SBAR Communication</h2>
          <p class="slide-intro">Standardized format for critical communication — provider calls, handoffs, rapid response activations.</p>
          <div class="overview-grid">
            <div class="overview-row">
              <span class="step-badge">S</span>
              <div><strong>Situation</strong> — who you are, patient name/room, what is happening NOW<span class="step-q">"Mrs. Smith in 412 is having acute respiratory distress."</span></div>
            </div>
            <div class="overview-row">
              <span class="step-badge">B</span>
              <div><strong>Background</strong> — admitting dx, relevant history, current meds, recent labs<span class="step-q">COPD exacerbation, admitted yesterday, on bronchodilators</span></div>
            </div>
            <div class="overview-row">
              <span class="step-badge">A</span>
              <div><strong>Assessment</strong> — your clinical judgment of the problem<span class="step-q">"I think she's having a COPD exacerbation."</span></div>
            </div>
            <div class="overview-row">
              <span class="step-badge">R</span>
              <div><strong>Recommendation</strong> — what you need from the provider<span class="step-q">"I need you to come evaluate her now and consider nebs/steroids."</span></div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="callout callout-tip">
            💡 SBAR is also used for bedside handoff reports and rapid response team notifications.
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- COLUMN 3: Therapeutic Communication -->
    <div class="slide-column">
      <div class="column-inner">
        <div class="slide">
          <div class="slide-number">3 / 8</div>
          <h2 class="slide-heading">🗣️ Therapeutic Communication</h2>
          <p class="slide-intro">Purposeful, patient-focused communication that promotes healing, trust, and understanding.</p>
          <div class="two-col">
            <div class="col-card">
              <h3 class="col-title">Therapeutic Techniques</h3>
              <ul class="bullet-list">
                <li><strong>Active listening</strong> — full attention, eye contact</li>
                <li><strong>Open-ended questions</strong> — "Tell me about your pain"</li>
                <li><strong>Reflection</strong> — mirrors patient's words/feelings</li>
                <li><strong>Clarification</strong> — "Can you explain what you mean?"</li>
                <li><strong>Focusing</strong> — directs to important topic</li>
                <li><strong>Silence</strong> — allows processing, conveys presence</li>
                <li><strong>Summarizing</strong> — confirms understanding</li>
                <li><strong>Sharing observations</strong> — "You seem anxious today"</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
            <div class="col-card">
              <h3 class="col-title">Barriers to Avoid</h3>
              <ul class="bullet-list">
                <li>False reassurance — "Everything will be fine"</li>
                <li>Giving unsolicited advice</li>
                <li>Closed questions (yes/no only)</li>
                <li>Changing the subject abruptly</li>
                <li>Judgmental or disapproving responses</li>
                <li>"Why" questions (feel accusatory)</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="optional-hint"><span class="arrow">↓</span><span>Non-therapeutic techniques to AVOID</span></div>
        </div>
        <div class="slide optional">
          <div class="back-hint"><span class="arrow">↑</span><span>Back to Therapeutic Communication</span></div>
          <div class="opt-inner">
            <h2 class="slide-heading">Non-Therapeutic Responses — Examples</h2>
            <div class="two-col">
              <div class="col-card">
                <h3 class="col-title">What NOT to Say → Better Alternative</h3>
                <ul class="bullet-list">
                  <li>"Don't worry" → "What concerns you most?"</li>
                  <li>"You should..." → "Some patients find it helpful to..."</li>
                  <li>"Why did you wait so long?" → "Tell me when this started"</li>
                  <li>"I know how you feel" → "This must be very difficult"</li>
                  <li>"Everything happens for a reason" → Sit quietly with the patient</li>
                  <li>"Are you in pain?" → "Describe any discomfort you're having"</li>
                </ul>
              </div>
              <div class="col-card">
                <h3 class="col-title">Crossed Communication Pitfalls</h3>
                <ul class="bullet-list">
                  <li><strong>Giving approval/disapproval</strong> — implies nurse judges behavior</li>
                  <li><strong>Defending</strong> — protecting the institution, not the patient</li>
                  <li><strong>Belittling feelings</strong> — "At least you don't have cancer"</li>
                  <li><strong>Probing</strong> — persistent questions beyond patient comfort</li>
                  <li><strong>Testing</strong> — challenging patient to prove point</li>
                </ul>
                <div class="callout" style="margin-top:0.75rem;">
                  Focus on the patient's <em>feelings</em>, not the facts of their situation.
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- COLUMN 4: Patient Teaching Methods -->
    <div class="slide-column">
      <div class="column-inner">
        <div class="slide">
          <div class="slide-number">4 / 8</div>
          <h2 class="slide-heading">📚 Patient Teaching Methods</h2>
          <p class="slide-intro">Assess readiness to learn <strong>before</strong> teaching. Choose the method that fits the patient's learning style.</p>
          <div class="two-col">
            <div class="col-card">
              <h3 class="col-title">Teaching Methods</h3>
              <ul class="bullet-list">
                <li><strong>Teach-back</strong> — gold standard; ask patient to explain in own words</li>
                <li><strong>Demonstration + Return demo</strong> — best for psychomotor skills (insulin injection)</li>
                <li><strong>Lecture/verbal</strong> — overview and explanations</li>
                <li><strong>Written materials</strong> — 6th-grade reading level</li>
                <li><strong>Visual aids</strong> — diagrams, videos, models</li>
                <li><strong>Group teaching</strong> — peer support, efficient</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
            <div class="col-card">
              <h3 class="col-title">Assess Readiness to Learn</h3>
              <ul class="bullet-list">
                <li><strong>Physical</strong> — pain-free, not fatigued, sensory intact</li>
                <li><strong>Emotional</strong> — anxiety reduces learning capacity</li>
                <li><strong>Cognitive</strong> — literacy, language, developmental level</li>
                <li><strong>Motivational</strong> — patient values the information</li>
              </ul>
              <h3 class="col-title" style="margin-top:0.75rem;">Documentation</h3>
              <ul class="bullet-list">
                <li>What was taught</li>
                <li>Method used</li>
                <li>Patient response / understanding demonstrated</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- COLUMN 5: Delegation -->
    <div class="slide-column">
      <div class="column-inner">
        <div class="slide">
          <div class="slide-number">5 / 8</div>
          <h2 class="slide-heading">👥 Delegation — 5 Rights</h2>
          <p class="slide-intro">RN <strong>retains accountability</strong> for all delegated tasks. Delegation transfers responsibility, not accountability.</p>
          <div class="two-col">
            <div class="col-card">
              <h3 class="col-title">5 Rights of Delegation</h3>
              <ul class="bullet-list">
                <li><strong>Right Task</strong> — within UAP scope</li>
                <li><strong>Right Circumstance</strong> — stable patient</li>
                <li><strong>Right Person</strong> — competent UAP</li>
                <li><strong>Right Direction</strong> — clear instructions</li>
                <li><strong>Right Supervision</strong> — RN monitors outcomes</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
            <div class="col-card">
              <h3 class="col-title">CAN Delegate to UAP</h3>
              <ul class="bullet-list">
                <li>ADLs (bathing, grooming, feeding)</li>
                <li>Vital signs — stable patients</li>
                <li>Intake &amp; Output measurement</li>
                <li>Repositioning, ambulation assistance</li>
              </ul>
              <h3 class="col-title" style="margin-top:0.75rem;">CANNOT Delegate</h3>
              <ul class="bullet-list">
                <li>Assessment &amp; nursing judgment</li>
                <li>Care planning</li>
                <li>Patient/family teaching</li>
                <li>Medication administration</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="callout callout-tip">
            💡 RN accountability is NEVER delegated. If UAP reports abnormal finding, RN must assess personally.
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- COLUMN 6: Hand-Off Report & Documentation -->
    <div class="slide-column">
      <div class="column-inner">
        <div class="slide">
          <div class="slide-number">6 / 8</div>
          <h2 class="slide-heading">📝 Hand-Off &amp; Documentation</h2>
          <p class="slide-intro">Accurate handoff prevents errors. Documentation is the legal record of care.</p>
          <div class="two-col">
            <div class="col-card">
              <h3 class="col-title">Bedside Hand-Off Elements</h3>
              <ul class="bullet-list">
                <li>Name, age, diagnosis, code status</li>
                <li>Current vital signs &amp; trends</li>
                <li>Recent labs, imaging results</li>
                <li>Medications &amp; IV fluids</li>
                <li>Pending orders / procedures</li>
                <li>Family concerns &amp; psychosocial</li>
                <li>Safety risks (falls, allergies)</li>
                <li>Plan for next shift</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
            <div class="col-card">
              <h3 class="col-title">Documentation Rules</h3>
              <ul class="bullet-list">
                <li><strong>Late entry:</strong> label "Late Entry" with CURRENT date/time AND actual event time</li>
                <li><strong>NEVER</strong> backdate or alter records</li>
                <li><strong>Error correction (paper):</strong> single line through error, initial and date — never white-out</li>
                <li>Document <em>objective</em> findings, not opinions</li>
                <li>Avoid "patient appears to be drug-seeking"</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="callout">
            ⚖️ If it wasn't documented, it wasn't done — legally and professionally.
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- COLUMN 7: Cultural Competence -->
    <div class="slide-column">
      <div class="column-inner">
        <div class="slide">
          <div class="slide-number">7 / 8</div>
          <h2 class="slide-heading">🌍 Cultural Competence</h2>
          <p class="slide-intro"><strong>First step = cultural assessment.</strong> Ask about beliefs, practices, and preferences before assuming.</p>
          <div class="two-col">
            <div class="col-card">
              <h3 class="col-title">Cultural Assessment</h3>
              <ul class="bullet-list">
                <li>Health beliefs and practices</li>
                <li>Religious/spiritual practices</li>
                <li>Food restrictions and preferences</li>
                <li>Modesty and gender preferences</li>
                <li>Traditional/folk medicine use</li>
                <li>Language preference</li>
                <li>Decision-making (individual vs. family)</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
            <div class="col-card">
              <h3 class="col-title">Key Principles</h3>
              <ul class="bullet-list">
                <li>Use <strong>trained medical interpreter</strong> — not family members</li>
                <li>Cultural <strong>humility</strong> vs. competence — ongoing learning</li>
                <li>Avoid assumptions based on appearance</li>
                <li>PLISSIT model for sensitive topics</li>
              </ul>
              <div class="col-example" style="margin-top:0.5rem;">PLISSIT: Permission, Limited Information, Specific Suggestions, Intensive Therapy</div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="callout callout-tip">
            💡 Using family members as interpreters violates HIPAA and can lead to errors. Always request a trained medical interpreter.
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- COLUMN 8: Exam Tips -->
    <div class="slide-column">
      <div class="column-inner">
        <div class="slide slide-exam">
          <div class="slide-number">8 / 8</div>
          <h2 class="slide-heading">📝 Exam Tips &amp; Key Points</h2>
          <div class="tips-grid">
            <div class="tip-card"><span class="tip-icon">📋</span><span class="tip-text">SBAR = standardized communication for provider calls and handoffs</span></div>
            <div class="tip-card"><span class="tip-icon">❓</span><span class="tip-text">Open-ended questions first — invite full narrative response</span></div>
            <div class="tip-card"><span class="tip-icon">✅</span><span class="tip-text">Teach-back confirms understanding — patient explains in own words</span></div>
            <div class="tip-card"><span class="tip-icon">👥</span><span class="tip-text">RN cannot delegate accountability — ever</span></div>
            <div class="tip-card"><span class="tip-icon">⏱️</span><span class="tip-text">Late entry: note current time AND actual time of care</span></div>
            <div class="tip-card"><span class="tip-icon">🌍</span><span class="tip-text">Cultural assessment is the FIRST step with diverse patients</span></div>
            <div class="tip-card"><span class="tip-icon">📝</span><span class="tip-text">Document: what was taught AND patient's demonstrated response</span></div>
            <div class="tip-card"><span class="tip-icon">🚫</span><span class="tip-text">Never use family as interpreter — requires trained medical interpreter</span></div>
          </div>
          <div style="margin-top:1.5rem; text-align:center;">
            <a href={`${base}/private/d439/communication-teaching`} class="article-link">← Full Article</a>
            <a href={`${base}/private/d439`} class="article-link article-link-ghost">D439 Home</a>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

  </div>

  <style>
